</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="131" pageNumber="132" type="type">
<paragraph pageId="131" pageNumber="132">Type.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="131" pageNumber="132">
Based on 
<taxonomicName authorityName="R. R. Mill" authorityYear="2009" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Seddera" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Seddera semhaensis" order="Solanales" pageId="131" pageNumber="132" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="semhaensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="131" pageNumber="132">Seddera semhaensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
R.R.Mill
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="131" pageNumber="132" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="131" pageNumber="132">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="131" pageNumber="132">
Grey undershrub to 50 cm, branches straight and rigid, densely grey canescent when young, becoming more sparsely hirsute with age and reddish-brown in colour. Leaves shortly petiolate, 2.5-8 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.5-1.5 mm, narrowly lanceolate, subacute, cuneate at base, densely grey-sericeous; petioles 0.5-1 mm. Flowers solitary, axillary, subsessile; peduncle absent; bracteoles 4-5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1.5 mm, narrowly oblong-elliptic, densely pilose; pedicels 0.5 mm; outer sepals 6-6.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1.5 mm, oblong, acuminate; inner sepals shorter, scarious; corolla 7-8.5 mm long, white faintly flushed pink, midpetaline bands long-sericeous to base; filaments glandular at base; ovary pilose; style divided 4 mm above base, stigmas 0.75 mm, obovoid. Capsule pilose at apex; seeds glabrous.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="131" pageNumber="132" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="131" pageNumber="132">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="131" pageNumber="132">Endemic to Semha Island in the Socotra islands of Yemen.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="131" pageNumber="132" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="131" pageNumber="132">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="131" pageNumber="132">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="131" pageNumber="132">Miller</emphasis>
12511, the only specimen we have seen of this species, has a glabrous ovary and style.The sepals are shorter and narrower than in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vierh., Denkschr. Akad., Wien, Math. - Naturwiss Kl. 71: 416. 1907. (Vierhapper" authorityYear="1907" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus kossmatii" order="Solanales" pageId="131" pageNumber="132" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="kossmatii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="131" pageNumber="132">Convolvulus kossmatii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but the differences are not very great. These two species are very close and may prove to be conspecific.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
